@terrafirma9328 Lithium Ion batteries can do quite a bit of damage too. And the amount of steam, relative to the amount of reinforced metal housing makes quite a hard limit. In short, you could make something that could never explode given the size of the void inside where the steam would expand. It can be made extremely safe -- far safer than lithium ion batteries. My point was that his sentence parsed false, even assuming the more limited context. That limit has everything to do with atmospheric pressure. And that pressure variable is just that -- variable. We can keep putting more energy into the water beyond that 100 degree limit. The key is how do you get the energy back out of the system in the form of electricity? I can think of more than a couple ways of doing that, one which wouldn't even require moving parts. These guys seem to have already gone to a place that Robert leaves out of his possibilities:

``Our steam battery was designed to offer an alternative for storing energy collected as heat, for later retrieval as steam, which can be used to run a turbine to produce electricity. The energy can be stored indefinitely, and retrieved at any time, and rate of retrieval can vary according to need.

Calx Energetics' steam battery is composed of many individual thermochemical cells (pictured right), combined to form a total storage solution for energy. These thermochemical cells are arranged in an array to form a battery.``

@ThinkingandTinkering  - yes but fortunately we don't pay to fire the sun up,  ha ha...  
(oops, yes indeed - commercial silicone PV  is in that range)
PV has the simplicity of being able to convert electricity into very high "quality heat" - thermal solar needs lots of mechanics to achieve the same result (domestic hot  water is a good simple use of "cheap" solar thermal - anything more tends to cost $$).
